1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:11,520
Imagine giving a a super smart AI a million pages of your company's standard operating procedures. You'd think it would become your absolute best

2
00:00:09,040 --> 00:00:14,080
employee, right? Like capable of doing anything.

3
00:00:12,400 --> 00:00:17,320
>> the dream. You just feed it everything and assume it's going to work perfectly.

4
00:00:15,560 --> 00:00:25,200
>> Right, but the science shows it actually gets dumber. You hand it this massive encyclopedia and it acts like someone who just, you know, threw a giant

5
00:00:23,160 --> 00:00:26,640
instruction manual into a blender.

6
00:00:25,200 --> 00:00:32,720
>> It's a really fundamental misunderstanding of how these models actually process information.

7
00:00:30,760 --> 00:00:38,560
I mean, we we assume more context equals more capability, but in reality it just creates this massive attention dilution.

8
00:00:37,080 --> 00:00:43,120
>> And that is exactly what we are tearing apart today. Welcome to the deep dive.

9
00:00:41,480 --> 00:00:50,960
Today we're looking at the day three white paper from the five day of AI agents vibe coding intensive course by Google X Kaggle.

10
00:00:49,520 --> 00:00:52,000
>> It's a really fascinating read.

11
00:00:50,960 --> 00:00:59,400
>> It is. And you know, if you're a technical Kaggle competitor looking to squeeze every drop of performance out of your agent architecture, or even if

12
00:00:57,600 --> 00:01:07,160
you're just intensely curious about how AI actually executes complex tasks behind the scenes, this deep dive is absolutely for you.

13
00:01:05,280 --> 00:01:09,440
>> Yeah, there's a lot to unpack here.

14
00:01:07,160 --> 00:01:20,200
>> We are uncovering why dumping data into massive AI context windows is, frankly, a recipe for disaster. And why this simple lightweight primitive called an

15
00:01:16,920 --> 00:01:25,720
agent skill is quietly replacing the entire bloated multi-agent ecosystem.

16
00:01:23,960 --> 00:01:32,760
>> It's a massive paradigm shift. I mean, we spent the last few years building these incredibly complex networks of like manager agents and worker agents.

17
00:01:31,640 --> 00:01:34,280
>> whole swarm thing.

18
00:01:32,760 --> 00:01:41,440
>> Exactly, trying to brute force specialized behavior. But agent skills completely sidestep that complexity.

19
00:01:39,120 --> 00:01:48,160
They turn a single general purpose AI into a hyper specialist, but um only for the exact seconds you need it to be.

20
00:01:46,600 --> 00:01:56,280
>> Let's start with the physical anatomy of this, because when I first read the term agent skill, I pictured some uh really dense compiled binary code or a deep

21
00:01:54,920 --> 00:01:57,320
neural network weight adjustment.

22
00:01:56,280 --> 00:02:00,800
>> Oh yeah, like some complicated fine-tuning process.

23
00:01:58,600 --> 00:02:03,880
>> but it's actually shockingly simple at a structural level.

24
00:02:01,760 --> 00:02:07,600
>> It really is. At its core, an agent skill is literally just a folder on your file system.

25
00:02:06,880 --> 00:02:08,880
>> Wait, just a folder?

26
00:02:07,600 --> 00:02:10,520
>> Just a folder.

27
00:02:08,880 --> 00:02:15,520
Inside that folder, you have one mandatory markdown file called skill.md.

28
00:02:14,440 --> 00:02:16,760
And you can think of this as the brain of the skill.

29
00:02:16,200 --> 00:02:19,480
>> Okay.

30
00:02:16,760 --> 00:02:23,800
>> It contains the metadata. So, the name and a very precise description of when to use it, along with the core instructions.

31
00:02:23,480 --> 00:02:25,640
>> Yeah.

32
00:02:23,800 --> 00:02:30,320
>> And then, around that file, you have optional subdirectories that handle all the heavy lifting.

33
00:02:28,640 --> 00:02:37,640
>> Right, I noticed the paper breaks down those subdirectories into three specific types. There's a scripts folder, a references folder, and an assets folder.

34
00:02:37,120 --> 00:02:38,880
>> Yeah.

35
00:02:37,640 --> 00:02:43,080
>> Why do we need all of those if the skill.md already has the instructions?

36
00:02:41,320 --> 00:02:47,400
>> Because you really want to separate the what to do from the how to do it deterministically.

37
00:02:46,800 --> 00:02:48,880
>> Oh, I see.

38
00:02:47,400 --> 00:02:56,760
>> The scripts folder holds actual executable code, like, you know, Python or bash scripts. If the agent needs to calculate a cryptographic hash, you

39
00:02:55,280 --> 00:02:58,640
don't want the language model guessing the math.

40
00:02:57,360 --> 00:03:00,600
>> Definitely not. You want it to just run a script.

41
00:02:59,320 --> 00:03:08,640
>> Exactly. Python script that does it perfectly every time. Then, the references folder is for dense domain context, like a 50-page PDF of tax

42
00:03:06,680 --> 00:03:17,320
codes, which is way too long for the main prompt. And the assets folder holds things like JSON schemas or email templates.

43
00:03:15,280 --> 00:03:20,880
The whole folder structure isolates the moving parts.

44
00:03:18,720 --> 00:03:26,440
>> And the paper outlines two distinct paths for how these skills actually get written in the real world.

45
00:03:24,360 --> 00:03:35,640
Path A is driven by subject matter experts. So, I'm picturing um an HR manager who has an onboarding guide, or maybe a compliance officer

46
00:03:34,440 --> 00:03:36,120
with a massive run book.

47
00:03:35,640 --> 00:03:38,440
>> Right.

48
00:03:36,120 --> 00:03:46,280
>> They don't need to learn Python. They just translate their existing human instructions into this skill.md format.

49
00:03:43,640 --> 00:03:51,320
>> Precisely. It really democratizes agent creation. You don't have to be a software engineer to build a skill.

50
00:03:49,680 --> 00:03:52,720
>> But path B is different, right?

51
00:03:51,320 --> 00:04:00,240
>> Yeah, path B comes from the developer side and it's much more dynamic. A developer might watch an agent successfully stumble through a really

52
00:03:58,240 --> 00:04:00,640
complex multi-step workflow.

53
00:04:00,240 --> 00:04:02,240
>> Okay.

54
00:04:00,640 --> 00:04:08,760
>> And they take that successful trace, clean up and crystallize it into a reusable skill folder. Next time the agent doesn't have to burn compute

55
00:04:07,440 --> 00:04:09,800
figuring it all out from scratch.

56
00:04:08,760 --> 00:04:12,080
>> It sounds a lot like a restaurant kitchen.

57
00:04:10,400 --> 00:04:14,280
>> A restaurant kitchen, how so?

58
00:04:12,080 --> 00:04:21,480
>> Well, the skill.md metadata is essentially the menu out front. The agent, our chef, reads the menu to know what's available.

59
00:04:20,519 --> 00:04:23,280
>> Okay, I like that.

60
00:04:21,480 --> 00:04:32,240
>> chef doesn't actually plug in the blender, which would be our scripts folder, or read the exact grandma's recipe out of the references folder

61
00:04:30,240 --> 00:04:36,120
until a customer actually walks in and orders that specific dish.

62
00:04:34,120 --> 00:04:39,360
>> That is a highly accurate way to visualize it.

63
00:04:37,600 --> 00:04:43,000
The technical term the white paper uses for this is progressive disclosure.

64
00:04:41,600 --> 00:04:44,960
>> Progressive disclosure?

65
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:49,800
>> Yeah. You only reveal the complex mechanics of a task when the task is actively triggered.

66
00:04:48,280 --> 00:04:55,400
>> But wait, a lot of developers listening to this are probably screaming at their dashboards right now because they already use MCP, the model context

67
00:04:54,720 --> 00:04:55,880
protocol.

68
00:04:55,400 --> 00:04:58,720
>> Oh, sure.

69
00:04:55,880 --> 00:05:04,800
>> Or they just keep a giant agents.md file in their project root. Aren't those tools already doing this exact thing?

70
00:05:02,600 --> 00:05:10,440
>> It's a common confusion, actually, but the distinction is absolutely critical for system design.

71
00:05:08,520 --> 00:05:11,120
MCP gives an agent reach.

72
00:05:10,440 --> 00:05:13,680
>> Reach?

73
00:05:11,120 --> 00:05:20,200
>> Right. An MCP server acts as a bridge connecting your agent to an external system like pulling a record from Salesforce or, you know, querying a big

74
00:05:18,800 --> 00:05:21,720
query database.

75
00:05:20,200 --> 00:05:24,360
>> Okay, so it connects to the outside world.

76
00:05:22,120 --> 00:05:33,040
>> Exactly. A skill, on the other hand, gives the agent know-how. It's procedural memory. It's the step-by-step logic of what to do with that Salesforce

77
00:05:31,200 --> 00:05:34,960
record once you actually have it.

78
00:05:33,040 --> 00:05:42,640
>> So, the skill might say, "Here are the five steps to process a customer refund." And step two might be, "Use the MCP tool to check the database."

79
00:05:40,919 --> 00:05:43,720
>> Exactly that. They compose beautifully together.

80
00:05:43,160 --> 00:05:46,880
>> Mhm.

81
00:05:43,720 --> 00:05:50,640
>> And regarding the agent.md file, that is global, always on context.

82
00:05:49,040 --> 00:05:52,520
>> Like project-wide rules?

83
00:05:50,640 --> 00:05:57,640
>> Yeah, like telling the AI, always write your code in TypeScript. Skills are strictly on demand.

84
00:05:55,800 --> 00:06:04,920
>> That distinction brings us right into the token economics of this whole movement. Because if a skill is just a smartly organized folder, why did this

85
00:06:03,160 --> 00:06:12,760
specific architecture explode in popularity, especially with the vibe coding crowd? You hinted earlier at the issue with dumping a million pages into a model.

86
00:06:11,120 --> 00:06:17,960
>> Yeah, it solves a massive kind of hidden crisis in AI engineering known as context drought.

87
00:06:16,040 --> 00:06:20,160
>> Context drought, sounds gross.

88
00:06:17,960 --> 00:06:27,200
>> It is, computationally speaking. For a long time, the industry's naive assumption was that larger context windows would just magically solve all

89
00:06:26,040 --> 00:06:28,480
our orchestration problems.

90
00:06:27,200 --> 00:06:30,280
>> Just throw more context at it.

91
00:06:28,480 --> 00:06:39,600
>> Right. If you have a 1 million token window, just dump every tool, every instruction, every API spec into the system prompt, and let the model figure it out.

92
00:06:37,720 --> 00:06:50,080
>> But the paper references that famous lost in the middle study, and also a new 2025 study from Chroma research, they proved that across 18 different

93
00:06:47,520 --> 00:06:54,120
frontier models, performance degrades silently as the input grows.

94
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:58,040
>> Silently is the keyword there. You don't get an error message, it just gets dumber.

95
00:06:56,040 --> 00:07:05,760
>> Wow. So, even if the window can physically hold a million tokens, the model's accuracy, its ability to actually retrieve and use that

96
00:07:03,360 --> 00:07:08,280
information, drops off a cliff long before the window fills up.

97
00:07:06,880 --> 00:07:13,000
>> Because the attention mechanism literally gets diluted. Every extra token you add competes for the model's focus.

98
00:07:12,560 --> 00:07:14,800
>> Yeah.

99
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:18,600
>> If your system prompt is cluttered with your instructions for 50 different tools, and the user just says hello,

100
00:07:18,080 --> 00:07:21,480
>> Right.

101
00:07:18,600 --> 00:07:25,480
>> the model is wasting compute ignoring 49 irrelevant tools.

102
00:07:22,880 --> 00:07:32,840
>> So, progressive disclosure fixes this by keeping the noise out. If I have 50 workflows, I don't load them all, I just load the metadata, the trigger

103
00:07:31,919 --> 00:07:33,560
descriptions.

104
00:07:32,840 --> 00:07:35,240
>> Yes.

105
00:07:33,560 --> 00:07:39,560
>> And the paper notes that might only be about 4,000 tokens.

106
00:07:37,480 --> 00:07:48,440
When the user asks for a specific workflow, that single skill triggers and adds maybe 2,000 tokens for its active body.

107
00:07:46,320 --> 00:07:51,640
The other 49 stay completely hidden on the hard drive.

108
00:07:49,360 --> 00:07:57,680
>> You're taking 15,000 tokens of active heavy context and compressing it down to maybe 6,000.

109
00:07:56,040 --> 00:08:01,600
The white paper shows this achieves up to a 98% reduction in active context.

110
00:08:00,360 --> 00:08:03,040
>> 98%?

111
00:08:01,600 --> 00:08:08,160
>> Yeah, it's huge. The model stays incredibly sharp because it's only looking at what actually matters in that moment.

112
00:08:06,720 --> 00:08:12,360
>> Hold on, let me just I'm doing the math here. You said the metadata for 50 skills is 4,000 tokens.

113
00:08:11,720 --> 00:08:14,280
>> Roughly, yeah.

114
00:08:12,360 --> 00:08:22,200
>> If I'm an enterprise with 40,000 skills in my library, just reading the menu of metadata is going to blow out the context window anyway. How does

115
00:08:20,280 --> 00:08:25,560
progressive disclosure survive at a massive corporate scale?

116
00:08:23,600 --> 00:08:28,880
>> That's a great catch. At that scale, you don't even load all the metadata into the prompt.

117
00:08:27,960 --> 00:08:30,320
>> Oh, you don't?

118
00:08:28,880 --> 00:08:32,560
>> No, you use a lightweight retrieval system, a a rag pipeline.

119
00:08:31,880 --> 00:08:34,640
>> Okay.

120
00:08:32,560 --> 00:08:44,200
>> So, when the user types a prompt, a really fast embeddings model quickly scans the 40,000 skill descriptions, grabs the top five most relevant ones,

121
00:08:42,479 --> 00:08:47,400
and only passes those five to the agent's context window.

122
00:08:46,040 --> 00:08:49,000
>> Oh, wow.

123
00:08:47,400 --> 00:08:51,680
>> It's progressive disclosure taken to the next level.

124
00:08:49,680 --> 00:08:55,120
>> That completely reframes how I think about routing.

125
00:08:53,040 --> 00:08:57,240
But, let me ask you this.

126
00:08:55,120 --> 00:09:05,040
If we can just dynamically swap skills in and out of single agent, does that mean the traditional multi-agent architecture is dead?

127
00:09:02,240 --> 00:09:10,520
Do we not need a manager agent routing tasks to a swarm of specialist worker agents anymore?

128
00:09:08,920 --> 00:09:14,000
>> Multi-agent systems aren't dead, but their role is getting much, much narrower.

129
00:09:12,520 --> 00:09:15,960
>> Okay, when do you still use them?

130
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:19,400
>> You still need them for genuine asynchronous parallelism.

131
00:09:17,880 --> 00:09:22,720
Like having three agents research three different companies simultaneously.

132
00:09:21,400 --> 00:09:24,040
Or when you have differing security postures.

133
00:09:23,400 --> 00:09:25,640
>> Security posture?

134
00:09:24,040 --> 00:09:33,280
>> Yeah. So, if you have an HR agent that needs clearance to read salaries, and a marketing agent scraping public websites, you keep those as separate

135
00:09:31,600 --> 00:09:37,000
agents, so the marketing bot can't accidentally leak payroll data.

136
00:09:35,120 --> 00:09:39,000
>> That makes perfect sense from a security standpoint.

137
00:09:37,840 --> 00:09:42,240
>> almost everything else,

138
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:44,040
>> Mhm. the swarm approach is dying.

139
00:09:42,240 --> 00:09:47,960
Let's say you're a logistics company with a hundred different process variants for shipping freight.

140
00:09:47,360 --> 00:09:49,240
>> Right.

141
00:09:47,960 --> 00:10:00,000
>> Maintaining a hundred different sub-agents with a hundred deployments, memory stores, and complex routing layers is just an operational nightmare. One

142
00:09:58,040 --> 00:10:06,280
general purpose agent dynamically loading a hundred different skills from a folder is vastly more elegant.

143
00:10:04,280 --> 00:10:13,800
>> Which sounds amazing until you realize the danger zone we're entering. I mean, if anyone in the company can write a skill just by typing up a markdown file,

144
00:10:12,120 --> 00:10:15,440
it sounds like a recipe for absolute chaos.

145
00:10:14,440 --> 00:10:16,600
>> absolutely can be.

146
00:10:15,440 --> 00:10:23,080
>> If you're listening to this and you've ever watched your agent just completely ignore the custom tool you spent three hours writing, this next part is going

147
00:10:21,680 --> 00:10:25,440
to hit close to home.

148
00:10:23,080 --> 00:10:34,960
>> The reality is quite stark. The white paper references a 2025 study from Skills Bench that looked at real-world agent deployments. They found that 19%

149
00:10:32,480 --> 00:10:40,120
of poorly designed skills actually caused the agent to perform worse than having no skill at all.

150
00:10:39,040 --> 00:10:41,800
>> Wait, worse?

151
00:10:40,120 --> 00:10:45,880
>> It actively subtracted baseline capability from the foundation model.

152
00:10:43,480 --> 00:10:54,280
>> That's wild. And a Versel study found similar results, right? A 56% non-invocation rate, meaning more than half the time the agent just ignored the

153
00:10:51,880 --> 00:11:00,200
skill completely. So, how exactly are these skills failing so catastrophically?

154
00:10:58,120 --> 00:11:04,200
>> Well, the paper outlines four specific failure modes. First is trigger failure.

155
00:11:02,640 --> 00:11:07,240
Your description's too vague, so the wrong skill fires, or the right one just stays quiet.

156
00:11:06,920 --> 00:11:09,400
>> Okay.

157
00:11:07,240 --> 00:11:14,640
>> Second is execution failure. It triggers correctly, but the internal instructions are messy, so it produces wild tool calls or hallucinates data.

158
00:11:14,200 --> 00:11:16,520
>> Right.

159
00:11:14,640 --> 00:11:23,400
>> Third is token budget failure. This is when the skill author dumps a massive unoptimized PDS into the references folder, blowing up the context window,

160
00:11:22,120 --> 00:11:26,200
and ruining the agent's short-term memory.

161
00:11:24,040 --> 00:11:30,240
>> And the fourth one is regression, which honestly feels like the most insidious.

162
00:11:28,680 --> 00:11:39,040
You add a brand new skill to the library, and because its trigger phrase is too similar to an existing skill, it hijacks the routing.

163
00:11:36,720 --> 00:11:41,760
>> Yes. You break a system that used to work perfectly just by adding something new.

164
00:11:41,040 --> 00:11:43,280
>> Exactly.

165
00:11:41,760 --> 00:11:48,040
>> This is why the white paper heavily mandates evaluation-driven development or EDD.

166
00:11:46,920 --> 00:11:49,640
>> Right, EDD.

167
00:11:48,040 --> 00:11:56,800
>> Before you write a single line of your skill.md file, you must write three JSON evaluation cases.

168
00:11:54,440 --> 00:12:04,080
>> I love this concept. You have to define the input, the expected tools to be called, and the expected output format completely up front. If you don't know

169
00:12:02,680 --> 00:12:08,080
what success looks like, you really have no business writing the instructions.

170
00:12:05,760 --> 00:12:11,680
>> Yeah, exactly. You are testing the skill in isolation using a single skill sub-agent pattern.

171
00:12:11,240 --> 00:12:13,240
>> Okay.

172
00:12:11,680 --> 00:12:19,480
>> You give a blank agent only this one skill and run the JSON evals. But here's the critical part.

173
00:12:17,360 --> 00:12:24,760
How you score those evaluations matters immensely. The paper dives deep into trajectory scoring.

174
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:33,240
>> I want to stop and unpack trajectory scoring because the paper mentions modes like exact, in order, or in order.

175
00:12:30,640 --> 00:12:38,800
But like, if the user asks for a result and the agent delivers the correct final output, does it really matter how it got there?

176
00:12:37,280 --> 00:12:39,960
>> It matters more than the final output itself.

177
00:12:39,320 --> 00:12:42,560
>> Really?

178
00:12:39,960 --> 00:12:52,200
>> A 2026 analysis by Latitude found that if you only score the final output, you'll pass 20 to 50% more test cases than if you score the trajectory,

179
00:12:50,400 --> 00:12:54,440
meaning the specific sequence of tool calls.

180
00:12:52,800 --> 00:12:57,640
>> Wait, if it's passing more cases, isn't that a good thing? We want it to pass.

181
00:12:56,040 --> 00:13:00,520
>> Not if it's stumbling into the right answer through disastrous methods.

182
00:12:59,839 --> 00:13:02,920
>> Uh.

183
00:13:00,520 --> 00:13:07,080
>> Let's make this concrete. Imagine a user asks your customer service agent to refund my last order.

184
00:13:06,160 --> 00:13:08,640
>> Okay.

185
00:13:07,080 --> 00:13:15,040
>> The agent gets confused, pulls up the user's profile, accidentally deletes their shipping address, but then somehow successfully triggers the Stripe refund

186
00:13:14,440 --> 00:13:17,080
API.

187
00:13:15,040 --> 00:13:18,839
>> Oh, wow. That's terrible.

188
00:13:17,080 --> 00:13:24,720
>> Right. If you were using output-only scoring, the test passes. The user got their money. But the trajectory was a complete disaster.

189
00:13:24,160 --> 00:13:27,000
>> I see.

190
00:13:24,720 --> 00:13:31,280
>> Trajectory scoring looks at the exact sequence of actions.

191
00:13:28,920 --> 00:13:39,680
For a read-only skill, like summarizing a public document, maybe any order is fine. But for an action-allowed skill that touches production databases, you

192
00:13:37,440 --> 00:13:44,480
absolutely need exact or in-order trajectory scoring to catch that deleted address.

193
00:13:42,960 --> 00:13:52,400
>> So, if the model is just the engine block, I wouldn't let a brand new unproven engine drive my kids to school without testing the brakes in a

194
00:13:50,320 --> 00:13:58,040
controlled environment first. There has to be a staging area, right? Like a sandbox where these skills run without actually pressing the buy button in the

195
00:13:57,280 --> 00:13:59,440
real world.

196
00:13:58,040 --> 00:14:00,440
>> You're anticipating the demo-to-deploy gap.

197
00:13:59,880 --> 00:14:02,080
>> Right.

198
00:14:00,440 --> 00:14:10,160
>> Confidence always peaks during the local demo, but it completely shatters in production. Teams immediately blame the model for hallucinating, but it's rarely

199
00:14:08,680 --> 00:14:11,440
a model problem. It's an environmental fit problem.

200
00:14:10,920 --> 00:14:12,960
>> Yeah.

201
00:14:11,440 --> 00:14:19,640
>> And this brings us to one of the most staggering statistics in the entire white paper involving Claude code.

202
00:14:17,240 --> 00:14:23,280
>> Yes, the reverse engineering stat. This completely blew my mind.

203
00:14:21,120 --> 00:14:33,080
>> It's incredible. Researchers mapped the entire infrastructure of Claude code version 2.1.88, and they discovered that 98.4%

204
00:14:30,960 --> 00:14:36,040
of the agent's code base was purely operational infrastructure.

205
00:14:34,480 --> 00:14:37,280
>> 98.4%.

206
00:14:36,040 --> 00:14:45,000
>> Yeah. Things like permission classifiers, session storage, retry logic, context compaction pipelines.

207
00:14:42,600 --> 00:14:48,400
Only 1.6% of the code base was the actual prompt reasoning loop.

208
00:14:46,800 --> 00:14:50,720
>> 1.6%.

209
00:14:48,400 --> 00:14:58,520
The AI part of the AI agent is barely a rounding error. That proves your point completely. The foundation model is just a commodity. You can swap the engine out

210
00:14:56,400 --> 00:15:05,800
tomorrow if a cheaper one drops, but the agent skills, the guardrails, the infrastructure, that's the steering wheel and the transmission.

211
00:15:03,680 --> 00:15:09,839
>> Exactly. That is your durable proprietary asset, which is why we have the graduation ladder.

212
00:15:08,720 --> 00:15:11,240
>> Right, the staging area.

